Desktop - Class in ej.mwt
A desktop is the top-level object that can be displayed on a Display.
A desktop is built for a specific Display, and that relationship cannot be modified.
A desktop may be shown or hidden, but at most one desktop is shown per Display.
Desktop() - Constructor for class ej.mwt.Desktop
Creates a new desktop on the default display.
Identical to new Desktop(Display.getDefaultDisplay()).
Desktop(Display) - Constructor for class ej.mwt.Desktop
Creates a new desktop on the specified display.

Display - Class in ej.microui.io
A Display object represents a pixelated screen in the platform, and there is a display for each such pixelated screen.
Displayable - Class in ej.microui.io
Displayable is an abstract class which defines the very objects that can be shown on a Display.
A Displayable object is built for a specific Display which can not be changed afterwards.
Displayable(Display) - Constructor for class ej.microui.io.Displayable
The newly created displayable is built for the given Display and is hidden.
DisplayFont - Class in ej.microui.io
A DisplayFont defines how text is rendered on a Display.
DisplayFonts are never created by applications, but are rather retrieved from the implementation environment.

An application can get all available fonts with DisplayFont.getAllFonts(), or query for a particular font: in this case the implementation will return the most appropriate font matching the request.

The height gives the height of a line of text with the font.

drawCircle(int, int, int) - Method in class ej.microui.io.GraphicsContext
Draws the outline of a circle covering the rectangle specified by its diameter, using the current color and stroke style.

The center of the circle is defined as the center of the rectangle whose origin is at (x,y) (upper-left corner) and whose dimension is given by diameter.

If diameter is negative, nothing is drawn.

drawEllipse(int, int, int, int) - Method in class ej.microui.io.GraphicsContext
Draws the outline of a ellipse covering the specified rectangle, using the current color and stroke style.

The center of the ellipse is defined as the center of the rectangle whose origin is at (x,y) (upper-left corner) and whose dimension is given by width and height.

If either width or height is negative, nothing is drawn.
